    <stitle>T 444E Diesel Engine Diagnostics (NAVPAK) (1997) - SECTION 3.5: ELECTRONIC CONTROL SYSTEM DIAGNOSTICS,
        ACCELERATOR PEDAL POSITION SENSOR/IVS SWITCH (APS/IVS) - ENGINE COOLANT TEMPERATURE (ECT) SENSOR - FAULT
        DETECTION/MANAGEMENT
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="PROCTYPE" graphiccount="1">
        <title>FAULT DETECTION/MANAGEMENT</title>
        <para>An ECT signal that is detected out of range high or low by the ECM will cause the ECM to ignore the ECT
            signal and assume an engine coolant temperature of -29&#176;F (-20&#176;C) for starting and a temperature of
            180&#176; F (82&#176; C) for engine running conditions. The WARN lamp will also be illuminated as long as
            the fault condition exists.
        </para>
        <para>Refer to
            <emph type="BOLD">Figure
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1901750">3.49</hotlnk>
            </emph>
            for the engine coolant temperature sensor circuit diagram and
            <emph type="BOLD">Table
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1901751">3.13</hotlnk>
            </emph>
            for the voltage checks.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1901750" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="eg7375" filename="../figeg7/eg7375.webp" type="webp"/>
            <caption>Figure 3.49 Engine Coolant Temperature Sensor Circuit Diagram</caption>
        </figure>
        <specpara>
            <note>
                <para>
                    <emph type="underscr">After removing connectors always check for damaged pins, corrosion, loose
                        terminals etc.
                    </emph>
                </para>
            </note>
        </specpara>
